    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u just give me the actual math formulas? i need to be specific for the report. specifically how does the shrinkage amount change the numerator vs the denominator in the turnover formula?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The formula itself is simple, but the *numbers* you plug in are where the magic—or in this case, the necessary accounting—happens. You need to make sure your figures are as honest as a freshly picked batch of raw materials, or you'll end up with a report that smells like old, forgotten cheese.\n\nThe standard Inventory Turnover Ratio is:\n\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nHere is how shrinkage specifically impacts the numerator and the denominator:\n\n**1. Impact on the Numerator (Cost of Goods Sold - COGS):**\n\nSince shrinkage represents inventory that was lost (stolen, damaged, misplaced), it means that the *actual* cost of goods you sold is higher than what your initial sales figures suggest.\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted COGS} = \\text{Reported Sales} - \\text{Shrinkage Amount}$$\n\n*   **Why this matters:** If you don't subtract the shrinkage, your COGS is artificially low. This makes your turnover ratio look better than it is, suggesting you are moving inventory faster than you actually are. Shrinkage is like a",
      "source": "target",
